sec.p:
To identify the two subpopulations of lowly and highly expressed genes, GSECA models the bimodal distribution of RNA-seq expression profile x of all protein-coding genes of a given sample i as a mixture of two Gaussian probability densities Φ, as previously proposed (18):(1)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}$$\begin{equation*}f({{{x}}_{{i}}}) = {\lambda _1}\phi ({{{x}}_1};{\mu _1},{\sigma _1}) + {\lambda _2}\phi ({{{x}}_1};{\mu _2},{\sigma _2})\end{equation*}$$\end{document}where λ is the mixing proportion, μ and σ are the mean and the standard deviation, respectively (26). To estimate the parameters μ and σ of the two components the method applies the Expectation–Maximization (EM) algorithm (26,27). The algorithm runs iteratively until the maximum likelihood of the parameters of the two components is reached. To ensure a consistent subdivision with the overall expression profile an additional heuristic step was implemented. In particular, GSECA requires the mean of the first component (i.e. highly expressed genes) to be greater than the mean of the second one (i.e. lowly expressed genes). The EM step is repeated until the condition is satisfied. Besides providing an estimate of the Gaussian components, the mixture model calculates the posterior probabilities τ of the component membership of the mixture (26). Thus, GSECA measures the probabilities τ1 and τ2 of each gene to belong to the two distributions defined by the two components.

After discretizing the gene expression levels into seven expression classes, GSECA implements a statistical framework to detect altered gene sets between the two groups of samples A and B. First, for each gene g and each EC c, the number of samples in which g is and is not assigned to the class c, n and r, respectively, are calculated for the two cohorts as follows:(2)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
